<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-04-16T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-04-16T15:00:00-05:00" n="123" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d123">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00/834: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-16T23:00:00+03:00">April 16,
                                    1939—11 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received April 16—8:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>184. Following is the text in translation of telegram from Kalinin<note n="8" xml:id="d123fn8">President of the Presidium of the Supreme
                                Council of the Soviet Union.</note> to the President released to the
                            press tonight: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Mr. President: I consider it a pleasant duty to express to you
                                    deep sympathy as well as hearty congratulations in regard to the
                                    noble appeal which you have sent to the Governments of Germany
                                    and Italy. You may be sure that your initiative finds the
                                    warmest response in the hearts of the peoples of the Soviet
                                    Socialist Union who are sincerely interested in the preservation
                                    of universal peace. Signed Kalinin.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>